Posted: Mon Oct 10, 2011 11:35 pm
I got propane but need to get some hose clamps to get it all hooked up. Quick question: I'm running kits for my first batches and they call for boiled water into the fermenter before the wort is made. There's no harm in making wort from the full 6 gallons (roughly) if I've got the space, right?
Pysgard
"Whoa."
Ars Praefectus
et Subscriptor
Tribus: 1NeJ69eo4aGGNoVwCAZ7nNy3GMYMGC1DSm
Registered: Oct 11, 2003Posts: 3174
Posted: Tue Oct 11, 2011 6:05 am
Nutrimentia wrote:I got propane but need to get some hose clamps to get it all hooked up. Quick question: I'm running kits for my first batches and they call for boiled water into the fermenter before the wort is made. There's no harm in making wort from the full 6 gallons (roughly) if I've got the space, right?Well, there's very little that will actively harm a brew. In the case of doing a full boil for a kit that calls for a partial, there are three things I can think of that are affected by a thinner boil. In order of descending importance: 1. Increased hop bitterness. Hop utilization is a function of the inverse of boil gravity. The lower the boil gravity, the higher the hop utilization and vice versa. Adding water lower's gravity, so you will end up with a more bitter end result. This is decreasingly important the shorter a hop addition is boiled, so it applies mostly to the 60 minute addition, somewhat to the 30 minute, and barely at all to the 5 minute. You can simply move the bittering addition forward to counteract most of the overbittering.2. Steeping grain tannin extraction. Much like boiled tea, barley husks contain tannin that is released proportionate to temperature and inversely proportional to gravity. This is similar to hop utilization, except it's an entirely undesirable characteristic in beer. Either steep at lower temps, or steep in smaller volume then top off.3. Slightly reduced wort color. This probably matters very little, but again, wort will darken somewhat as an inverse function of boil gravity. Not even worth thinking about, most likely.
